Use `@intFromPtr` and `% @alignOf(...)`.

For `replacement_buffer: [*]u16`, assert both non-null and alignment before casting to `*[buffer_effective_length]u16`:

```zig
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_buffer) != 0);
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_buffer) % @alignOf([buffer_effective_length]u16) == 0);
```

For `replacement_count: *u8`:

```zig
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_count) != 0);
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_count) % @alignOf(u8) == 0);
```

But note: `@alignOf(u8)` is `1`, so the second `replacement_count` assert is always true for any non-null pointer. It is still structurally consistent, but not useful.

In the exported wrapper, the full assertion block would look like:

```zig
// Replacement buffer must not be null.
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_buffer) != 0);
// Replacement buffer must be aligned for the fixed UTF-16 replacement array.
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_buffer) % @alignOf([buffer_effective_length]u16) == 0);

// Replacement count pointer must not be null.
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_count) != 0);
// Replacement count pointer alignment is trivial for u8, but keep the check for consistency.
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_count) % @alignOf(u8) == 0);
```

Then the fixed-array pointer conversion would be:

```zig
const rb: *[buffer_effective_length]u16 = @ptrCast(@alignCast(replacement_buffer));
```

One nuance: `@alignOf([buffer_effective_length]u16)` is the same as `@alignOf(u16)`, because array alignment equals element alignment. So this also works:

```zig
assert(@intFromPtr(replacement_buffer) % @alignOf(u16) == 0);
```

I prefer the array form because it documents the intended cast target.
